Gender and social media use

Dipankar Lahiri

2025-02-27

This is an analysis of a sample dataset of 2189 individuals sourced from the 2017 British Election Study Data. The 2189 individuals were classified on Gender into Male and Female. Their responses on use of Facebook and Twitter respectively were entered as binary nominal variables.

Hypotheses 1: There is an association between gender and social media use.

Gender and Facebook

chisq.test(
  x = my_df$Gender,
  y = my_df$Use_Facebook
)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  my_df$Gender and my_df$Use_Facebook
## X-squared = 18.046, df = 1, p-value = 0.00002156
my_df %>%
  ggplot (aes(x=Gender, fill = Use_Facebook)) + geom_bar (position = 'dodge')

Gender and Twitter

chisq.test(
  x = my_df$Gender,
  y = my_df$Use_Twitter
)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  my_df$Gender and my_df$Use_Twitter
## X-squared = 0.70466, df = 1, p-value = 0.4012
my_df %>%
  ggplot (aes(x=Gender, fill = Use_Twitter)) + geom_bar (position = 'dodge')

Findings - A Pearsons Chi-Square test of independence shows a significant positive relationship between Gender and Facebook usage, (1, N = 2189) = 18.05, p < 0.001.

On the other hand, a Pearsons Chi-Square test shows no significant relationship between Gender and Twitter usage, (1, N = 2189) = 0.705, p = 0.401 (p>0.05).

Twitter and Facebook use

chisq.test(
  x= my_df$Use_Facebook,
  y= my_df$Use_Twitter
)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  my_df$Use_Facebook and my_df$Use_Twitter
## X-squared = 175.13, df = 1, p-value < 0.00000000000000022
my_df %>% ggplot(aes(x = Use_Facebook, fill = Use_Twitter)) + geom_bar (position = 'dodge')

# A Pearsons Chi-Square test of independence shows a significant positive relationship between Facebook use and Twitter use, (1, N = 2189) = 175.13, p < 0.001.

We know now that Gender and Twitter use both have significant relationships with Facebook use. The Twitter-Facebook relationship seems to be stronger than the Gender-Facebook relationship based on a higher X value returned in the Chi-Square test. Lets explore these two relationships further with Fishers exact test for count data.

fisher.test(
  x = my_df$Gender,
  y = my_df$Use_Facebook
)
## 
##  Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data
## 
## data:  my_df$Gender and my_df$Use_Facebook
## p-value = 0.00002122
## alternative hypothesis: true odds ratio is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.5790543 0.8201241
## sample estimates:
## odds ratio 
##  0.6892201
fisher.test(
  x = my_df$Use_Twitter,
  y = my_df$Use_Facebook
)
## 
##  Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data
## 
## data:  my_df$Use_Twitter and my_df$Use_Facebook
## p-value < 0.00000000000000022
## alternative hypothesis: true odds ratio is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   5.312226 10.675286
## sample estimates:
## odds ratio 
##   7.449831

Findings: A Fishers exact test shows a significant negative relationship between Gender and Facebook use, OR = 0.69, 95% CI [0.58, 0.82], p < 0.001, suggesting that men are 31% less likely than women to use Facebook. A Fishers exact test shows a significant positive relationship between Twitter use and Facebook use, OR = 7.45, 95% CI [5.31, 10.68], p < 0.001, suggesting that those who use Twitter are more than 7 times more likely to use Facebook as well.

Linear regression

my_df <- my_df %>%
  mutate(
    Gender = factor(Gender),
    Use_Facebook = factor(Use_Facebook, levels = c("No", "Yes")),
    Use_Twitter = factor(Use_Twitter, levels = c("No", "Yes")) 
  )

model <- glm(Use_Facebook ~ Gender + Use_Twitter, data = my_df, family = binomial)

summary(model)
##

## glm(formula = Use_Facebook ~ Gender + Use_Twitter, family = binomial, 
##     data = my_df)

my_df$Predicted_Prob <- predict(model, type = "response")
head(my_df[, c("Gender", "Use_Twitter", "Predicted_Prob")])

new_data <- data.frame(
  Gender = factor(c("Male", "Male", "Female", "Female"), levels = c("Male", "Female")),
  Use_Twitter = factor(c("No", "Yes", "No", "Yes"), levels = c("No", "Yes"))
)

new_data$Predicted_Prob <- predict(model, newdata = new_data, type = "response")

new_data
##   Gender Use_Twitter Predicted_Prob
## 1   Male          No      0.4497752
## 2   Male         Yes      0.8624882
## 3 Female          No      0.5570495
## 4 Female         Yes      0.9060972
ggplot(new_data, aes(x = interaction(Gender, Use_Twitter), y = Predicted_Prob, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(x = "Gender & Twitter Use", y = "Predicted Probability of Facebook Use", title = "Predicted Probabilities of Facebook Use") +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(new_data, aes(x = interaction(Gender, Use_Twitter), y = Predicted_Prob, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge", width = 0.6) +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(Predicted_Prob, 2)), vjust = -0.5) +
  labs(x = "Gender & Twitter Use", y = "Predicted Probability of Facebook Use", title = "Predicted Probabilities of Facebook Use") +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(new_data, aes(x = Gender, y = Use_Twitter, fill = Predicted_Prob)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "blue") +
  labs(x = "Gender", y = "Twitter Use", fill = "Probability", title = "Predicted Probabilities of Facebook Use") +
  theme_minimal()

Process: A binary logistic regression model was conducted to predict Facebook usage based on Gender and Twitter usage. The model was statistically significant, (2, N = 2189) = 224.7, p < 0.001, indicating that the predictors explained a significant portion of variance in Facebook usage. The Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) was 2771, suggesting an improved model fit compared to the null model (AIC = 2989.7).

Findings

The likeliest person in our sample to be a Facebook user is a Twitter-using Female (90.6% predicted probability) and the least likely person to be a Facebook user is a non-Twitter-using Male (45% predicted probability).

Gender: Men were significantly less likely to use Facebook than women ( = -0.431, p < 0.001). The odds of Facebook use for men were 35% lower compared to women (OR = 0.65, 95% CI: 0.54 - 0.78). The predicted probability of Facebook use was ~55.7% for women and ~44.9% for men, holding Twitter usage constant.

Twitter Usage: Those who used Twitter were significantly more likely to use Facebook ( = 2.038, p < 0.001). Twitter users had 7.67 times higher odds of using Facebook compared to non-Twitter users (OR = 7.67, 95% CI: 5.48 - 10.73).

Twitter users are more likely to use Facebook even after controlling for Gender. Gender also has an independent effect on Facebook use.
